 I give this anecdote here, because Diterlizzis message in "Say What?" is that we cannot ever truly know what animals say to one another. But there is, in fact, a reasonable bit of research into non-human communication, so that we do know at least a little about what animals express to one another - and, as I say, when you begin to listen closely you can begin to understand some of its language for yourself. But "Say What?" does not encourage this kind of attentive listening. While I appreciate that Diterlizzi is trying to engage kids in thinking about what animals are expressing, I find her approach anthropocentric. She dresses her animals up, placing them in human houses, and putting them in human situations (such as reaching for food from the fridge or having a bath in the tub), then describes the way non-human animals communicate as "silly" and employs the word "Say" as if animals could or should talk as humans do. She is suggesting that animals must somehow want to express human concepts, and that the kids who read this book should think of animals through relating to them as people, rather than encouraging her readers to listen to the animals themselves without trying to anthropomorphize them. I find this to be really disappointing. 
